#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:93
msgid "This will pull up root user's `crontab` as it exists at this moment in your chosen editor, and may look something like this. Go ahead and read through this commented version, as it contains descriptions of each field that we will be using next:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Fenced code block
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:94
#, no-wrap
msgid "# Edit this file to introduce tasks to be run by cron.\n"
"#\n"
"# Each task to run has to be defined through a single line\n"
"# indicating with different fields when the task will be run\n"
"# and what command to run for the task\n"
"#\n"
"# To define the time you can provide concrete values for\n"
"# minute (m), hour (h), day of month (dom), month (mon),\n"
"# and day of week (dow) or use '*' in these fields (for 'any').\n"
"#\n"
"# Notice that tasks will be started based on the cron's system\n"
"# daemon's notion of time and timezones.\n"
"#\n"
"# Output of the crontab jobs (including errors) is sent through\n"
"# email to the user the crontab file belongs to (unless redirected).\n"
"# cron\n"
"# For example, you can run a backup of all your user accounts\n"
"# at 5 a.m every week with:\n"
"# 0 5 * * 1 tar -zcf /var/backups/home.tgz /home/\n"
"#\n"
"# For more information see the manual pages of crontab(5) and cron(8)\n"
"#\n"
"# m h  dom mon dow   command\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:121
msgid "Notice that this particular `crontab` file has some of its own documentation built-in. That is not always the case. When modifying a `crontab` on a container or minimalist operating system, the `crontab` will be an empty file unless an entry is in it."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:123
msgid "Assume that you have a backup script that you want to run at 10 PM at night. The `crontab` uses a 24 hour clock, this would be 22:00. Assume that the backup script is called \"backup\" and that it is currently in the _/usr/local/sbin_ directory."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:127
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Remember that this script needs to also be executable (`chmod +x`) in order for the `cron` to run it.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:129
msgid "To add the job, you:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:133
msgid "`crontab` stands for \"cron table\" and the format of the file is, in fact, a loose table layout. Now that you are in the `crontab`, go to the bottom of the file and add your new entry. If you are using `vi` as your default system editor, then this is done with the following keys:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:135
msgid "`Shift : $`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:137
msgid "Now that you are at the bottom of the file, insert a line and type a brief comment to describe what is going on with your entry. This is done by adding a \"#\" to the beginning of the line:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:139
msgid "`# Backing up the system every night at 10PM`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:141
msgid "Now hit enter. You should still be in the insert mode, so the next step is to add your entry. As shown in our empty commented `crontab` (above) this is **m** for minutes, **h** for hours, **dom** for day of month, **mon** for month, and **dow** for day of week."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:143
msgid "To run our backup script every day at 10:00, the entry would look like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:145
#, no-wrap
msgid "`00  22  *  *  *   /usr/local/sbin/backup`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:147
msgid "This says run the script at 10 PM, every day of the month, every month, and every day of the week. This is a simplistic example and things can get quite complicated when you need specifics."
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:148
#, no-wrap
msgid "The @options for `crontab`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:151
msgid "Another way to run jobs at a strictly scheduled time (i.e., day, week, month, year, and so on.) is to use the @options, which offer the ability to use more natural timing. The @options consist of:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:158
msgid "`@hourly` runs the script every hour of every day at 0 minutes past the hour. (this is exactly the result of placing your script in `/etc/cron.hourly` too)"
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:158
msgid "`@daily` runs the script every day at midnight."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:158
msgid "`@weekly` runs the script every week at midnight on Sunday."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:158
msgid "`@monthly` runs the script every month at midnight on the first day of the month."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:158
msgid "`@yearly` runs the script every year at midnight on the first day of January."
msgstr ""

#. type: Bullet: '* '
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:158
msgid "`@reboot` runs the script on system startup only."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:162
#, no-wrap
msgid "    Using these `crontab` entries bypasses the `anacron` system and reverts to the `crond.service` whether `anacron` is installed or not.\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:164
msgid "For our backup script example, if we use the @daily option to run the backup script at midnight, the entry would look like this:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:166
msgid "`@daily /usr/local/sbin/backup`"
msgstr ""

#. type: Title ###
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:167
#, no-wrap
msgid "More Complex Options"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:170
msgid "So far, everything we have talked about has had pretty simplistic options, but what about the more complex task timings? Say that you want to run your backup script every 10 minutes during the day (probably not a practical thing to do, but hey, this is an example!). To do this you would write:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:172
#, no-wrap
msgid "`*/10  *   *   *   *   /usr/local/sbin/backup`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:174
msgid "What if you wanted to run the backup every 10 minutes, but only on Monday, Wednesday, and Friday?:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:176
#, no-wrap
msgid "`*/10  *   *   *   1,3,5   /usr/local/sbin/backup`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:178
msgid "What about every 10 minutes every day except Saturday and Sunday?:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:180
#, no-wrap
msgid "`*/10  *   *   *    1-5    /usr/local/sbin/backup`\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:182
msgid "In the table, the commas lets you specify individual entries within a field, and the dash lets you specify a range of values within a field. This can happen in any of the fields, and on many fields at the same time. As you can see, things can get pretty complicated."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: ../src/docs/guides/automation/cron_jobs_howto.md:184
msgid "When determining when to run a script, you need to take time and plan it out, particularly if the criteria are complex."
msgstr ""

